title: A Multi-centre, Double-blind, Parallel-group, Randomised Controlled Study to Investigate Efficacy and Safety of Orally Administered BI 425809 During a 12-week Treatment Period Compared to Placebo in Patients With Cognitive Impairment Due to Alzheimer's Disease.
description_brief: The study is designed to compare the effects of BI 425809 compared to placebo in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer's Disease.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails:
Subjects were screened prior to participation and attended a specialist site which ensured that they strictly met all inclusion/exclusion criteria. Subjects were not to be allocated to a treatment group if any of the criteria were violated.

One subject was randomized by error via Interactive Response Technology (IRT) but never took a drug.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: This is a multi-centre, double-blind, parallel-group, randomised controlled study to investigate efficacy and safety of orally administered BI 425809 during a 12-week treatment period compared to placebo in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer's Disease.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive Subscale 11 Item (ADAS-Cog11) Total Score After 12 Weeks of Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description:
The ADAS-Cog11 is an 11-item cognitive subscale that objectively measures memory, language, orientation and praxis with a total score range of 0 to 70, with lower scores indicating less severe impairment. A negative change indicates an improvement from baseline.

Multiple comparison procedures and modelling (MCPmod) in combination with mixed model repeated measures (MMRM) is used for primary analysis of the primary endpoint.

MMRM included fixed, categorical covariates of treatment, visit, baseline Mini Mental State Examination MMSE (\>=20, \<20) and treatment-by-visit interaction, as well as the continuous fixed covariates of baseline and baseline-by-visit interaction. Patient was considered as random effect. The unstructured covariance structure was used to model the within patient measurements. The same MMRM model used in the primary analysis is used for the secondary analysis of the primary endpoint.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in the Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study/Activities of Daily Living (ADCS-ADL) Score After 12 Weeks of Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description:
Change from baseline in the ADCS-ADL score after 12 weeks of treatment is presented.

The ADCS-ADL is a rating scale used to assess basic and instrumental activities of daily living. In the full version of the scale, 23 items are rated by the investigator using information supplied by the caregiver. Each item has a score range varying from 0-3 to 0-5. The sum score could range from 0 to 78, with higher scores indicating less severe impairment. A positive change indicates an improvement from baseline.

Abbreviation: MMSE = Mini Mental State Examination

outcomeMeasures.title: Clinician's Interview-Based Impression of Change (CIBIC+) Score After 12 Weeks of Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description:
Clinician's Interview-Based Impression of Change (CIBIC+) score is based on semi-structured interview covering domains of function and cognition. It additionally requires the assessment of psychiatric signs and symptoms. The patient and their caregiver are interviewed and questioned by the clinician. Change rate is based on an unanchored 7-point scale (with 0 being not assessed, 1-3 being very much improved to minimally improved, 4 being no change, and 5-7 being minimally worse to very much worse).

For the ANCOVA model, the baseline value for CIBIC+ is represented by CIBIS which is clinician's interview-based impression of severity score (scores range from 0-7, with 0 being not assessed, 1 being normal, and 7 being most extremely ill) in order to adjust for potential baseline heterogeneity.

Abbreviation: MMSE = Mini Mental State Examination

Such review will be done with regard to proprietary information, information related to patentable inventions, medical, scientific, and statistical accuracy within 60 days. BI may request a delay of the publication in order to protect BI's intellectual property rights.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational drug BI 425809 is a potent, selective glycine transporter‑1 (GlyT1) inhibitor that increases glycine in CSF to potentiate NMDA‑receptor function and thereby aims to improve cognition (symptomatic cognitive enhancement), not to remove amyloid or tau pathology. citeturn0search3turn0search0

Act: Extracted trial details — multi‑centre, double‑blind, randomized, 12‑week oral BI 425809 vs placebo in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer’s disease; the same molecule has been tested in phase II Alzheimer’s and schizophrenia cognition trials. These trials report target engagement (increased CSF glycine) and cognitive endpoints rather than amyloid/tau biomarker removal. citeturn0search6turn0search1turn0search3

Reflect: Classification check — under the provided definitions, BI 425809 is a small‑molecule symptomatic cognitive enhancer (it is not a biologic, nor a small molecule directed at canonical AD pathology such as amyloid or tau, nor is it primarily for neuropsychiatric/behavioral symptoms). Therefore the correct category is 'cognitive enhancer'. Supporting clinical evidence of cognitive benefit (and dose selection) comes from RCTs in AD and schizophrenia. citeturn0search5turn0search6

Web search sources (key references used): PubMed/first‑in‑human and PK/PD studies describing BI 425809 as a GlyT1 inhibitor and CSF glycine increase; phase II randomized trials in Alzheimer’s disease and in schizophrenia assessing cognition. citeturn0search0turn0search3turn0search1turn0search6turn0search5
explanation_agent: Reason: BI 425809 (iclepertin) is a selective glycine transporter‑1 (GlyT1) inhibitor that raises glycine levels in CSF to potentiate NMDA‑receptor function and thereby aims to improve cognition (symptomatic enhancement rather than removing amyloid or tau). citeturn0search4turn0search3

Act: Extracted trial details — a multicentre, double‑blind, randomized, 12‑week oral BI 425809 vs placebo study in patients with cognitive impairment due to Alzheimer’s disease; endpoints and prior trials focused on cognitive outcomes and target engagement (increased CSF glycine), not amyloid/tau biomarker removal. Based on the mechanism (modulation of glycine/NMDA neurotransmission) the most specific CADRO match is D) Neurotransmitter Receptors. citeturn0search2turn0search5

Reflect: Classification check — GlyT1 inhibition modulates synaptic neurotransmission by altering availability of the NMDA receptor co‑agonist glycine, fitting squarely within CADRO's Neurotransmitter Receptors category (rather than amyloid, tau, inflammation, or a multi‑target/interventional diagnostic). No evidence in the description that the drug targets amyloid/tau, ApoE/lipids, vasculature, or primarily neuroprotection pathways; therefore D) Neurotransmitter Receptors is appropriate. citeturn0search1turn0search4

Web search results (key sources): 1) Translational PK/PD study showing BI 425809 is a potent/selective GlyT1 inhibitor and increases glycine in CSF (target engagement). citeturn0search4 2) First‑in‑human safety/PK study describing BI 425809 as a GlyT1 inhibitor developed for cognition (Alzheimer’s and schizophrenia rationale). citeturn0search3 3) Preclinical work showing dose‑dependent CSF glycine increase and cognition improvement in animal models. citeturn0search1 4) Phase II randomized controlled trial in Alzheimer’s disease (12‑week study) reporting cognitive endpoints and no clinically meaningful cognitive benefit overall. citeturn0search2turn0search5
